The KELT-15 Exoplanetary System


Overview

KELT-15 is a star with 2.06 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.78 times its radius. It is located NaN light years away from the solar system.

KELT-15 is known to have undefined exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the KELT-15 system


KELT-15 b

KELT-15 b was discovered by the undefined observatory using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.05 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of KELT-15 b is 416.58000000000004 times the mass of Earth. The radius of KELT-15 b is 19.504 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, KELT-15 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
